1. DEFINITIONS
"Confidential Information" means information (regardless of its form) disclosed or otherwise made available by or on behalf of the Discloser or its Related Entities to the Recipient or its Authorised Representatives, including before the date of this Agreement, for or in connection with the Purpose, which:
(a) is marked as being proprietary or confidential to the Discloser or its Related Entities, or that the Discloser has otherwise advised is proprietary or confidential to Discloser or its Related Entities;
(b) is confidential to a third party to whom the Discloser or its Related Entities owes an obligation of confidence, which obligation is notified to the Recipient or its Authorised Representatives; and/or
(c) in the circumstances surrounding disclosure or because of the nature of the information, ought in good faith to be treated as confidential,
and expressly includes:
(d) information that relates to or includes financial information, business plans, trade secrets, customers or suppliers of the Discloser or its Related Entities;
(e) the contents of this Agreement;
(f) the fact of or content of any discussions between the parties relating to the Purpose; and
(g) information created by the Recipient that is derived wholly or partly from the Confidential Information.
"Discloser" means the party disclosing or otherwise making available Confidential Information to the Recipient in relation to the Purpose.
"Excluded Information" means Confidential Information:
(a) which is in or becomes part of the public domain other than through a breach of this Agreement or an obligation of confidentiality owed to the Discloser;
(b) which the Recipient can prove was already known to it prior to or at the time of disclosure by the Discloser;
(c) which the Recipient can prove was independently developed by it prior to or at the time of disclosure by the Discloser; or
(d) which the Recipient acquires or acquired from a third party entitled to disclose it.
"Recipient" means the party receiving Confidential Information in relation to the Purpose.
"Related Entities" has the meaning given to it in the Corporations Act 2001 (Cth).

ACKNOWLEDGEMENT AND INDEMNITY
The Recipient acknowledges that: 
any breach of this Agreement may result in significant damage to the Discloser;
damages are not a sufficient remedy for the Discloser for any breach of this Agreement; and
the Discloser is entitled to specific performance or injunctive relief as a remedy for any breach or threatened breach by the Recipient.
information provided pursuant to this document Agreement may be ‘inside information’ for the purpose of the Corporations Act and agrees, if that is the case, that it will procure its Related Bodies Corporate that receive or are provided any Confidential Information to comply with Part 7.10, Division 3 of the Corporations Act in respect of any shares or securities in relation to the Confidential Information in accordance with this Agreement
Without limiting clause 3.1, the Recipient indemnifies the Discloser and its Related Entities against any cost, expenses, loss, damage or liability suffered by them as a consequence of any breach by the Recipient (including by its Authorised Representatives) of this Agreement.

RETURN OR DESTRUCTION OF CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION
Without in any way limiting the obligations of the Recipient under this Agreement, when the Confidential Information is no longer required by the Recipient for the Purpose (as advised by the Discloser), the Recipient will cease all use of the Confidential Information and the Discloser may request that the Recipient:
return the Confidential Information to the Discloser; or
destroy or delete (as applicable) the Confidential Information in a manner reasonably requested by the Discloser,
Clause 4.1 does not apply to, or require the return or destruction or deletion of, any legal advice, internal working papers, legal opinions or legal due diligence reports prepared for the Recipient, or Board minutes or papers relating to those issues.

DISCLAIMER
This Agreement does not obligate the Discloser to provide any information to the Recipient.  
The Recipient acknowledges that the Discloser does not make any representation or warranty as to the accuracy or completeness of the Confidential Information.  The Recipient agrees that it must satisfy itself as to the accuracy and completeness of Confidential Information.
To the maximum extent permitted by law, the Discloser disclaims all liability for any loss or damage suffered by any person accessing, using, disclosing or acting on any Confidential Information.

GENERAL
The failure of a party at any time to insist on performance of any provision of this Agreement is not a waiver of its right at any later time to insist on performance of that or any other provision of this Agreement.
A party will not assign or otherwise transfer any or all of its rights arising out of this Agreement without the prior written consent of the other party.  
This agreement may not be varied except in writing signed by the parties.
This Agreement is governed by the laws of New South Wales and each party submits to the non-exclusive jurisdiction of the Courts of New South Wales.
This Agreement may be executed in counterparts, each of which will be considered an original and all of which together constitute one and the same Agreement. Each party agrees that this Agreement and any other documents to be delivered in connection herewith may be electronically signed, and that any electronic signatures appearing on this Agreement or such other documents are the same as handwritten signatures for the purposes of validity, enforceability, and admissibility

RETURN OR DESTRUCTION OF CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION
Without in any way limiting the obligations of the Recipient under this Agreement, when the Confidential Information is no longer required by the Recipient for the Purpose (as advised by the Discloser), the Recipient will cease all use of the Confidential Information and the Discloser may request that the Recipient:
return the Confidential Information to the Discloser; or
destroy or delete (as applicable) the Confidential Information in a manner reasonably requested by the Discloser,
Clause 4.1 does not apply to, or require the return or destruction or deletion of, any legal advice, internal working papers, legal opinions or legal due diligence reports prepared for the Recipient, or Board minutes or papers relating to those issues.

Article 2 (Definition of Confidential Information)
The term “Confidential Information” as used in the Agreement shall mean Disclosing Party’s technical, commercial and other information disclosed by Disclosing Party to Receiving Party in connection with the Study.
Notwithstanding the provisions of the preceding paragraph, any information which Receiving Party can objectively demonstrate as falling under any of the following items shall not be included in Confidential Information.
information which is already in the public domain at the time of the disclosure by Disclosing Party, or information which becomes in the public domain through reasons not attributable to Receiving Party (including Entrusted Parties as defined in paragraph 4 of Article 3) after the disclosure by Disclosing Party;
information already in the possession of the Receiving Party at the time of the disclosure by Disclosing Party;
information developed or generated independently by Receiving Party without using Confidential Information of Disclosing Party; or,
information obtained by Receiving Party through a third party having the legitimate authority without obligation of confidentiality.
Notwithstanding the provisions of paragraph 1, ThoughtSpot and YAMATO shall treat the contents, existence and results of the Study (including the Agreement itself) as Confidential Information.

Article 3 (Handling of Confidential Information)
Receiving Party shall handle Confidential Information with the duty of care and diligence of a good manager, and without the prior written consent of Disclosing Party, shall not disclose, announce, provide or divulge Confidential Information to any third party. 
Receiving Party shall not use Confidential Information for any purpose other than the Study or beyond the scope necessary for the Study.
Receiving Party may disclose Confidential Information to officers and employees of its own which to the minimum extent necessary for the Study.  In such event, Receiving Party shall require such officers and employees to maintain obligations equivalent to the confidentiality obligations of Receiving Party hereunder, and shall be liable for any damage caused to Disclosing Party due to a breach of the Agreement by such officers and employees.
In the event Receiving Party discloses Confidential Information to a third party (including the party entrusted by Receiving Party) upon the consent of Disclosing Party as referred to in paragraph 1 (hereinafter referred to as “Entrusted Party”), Receiving Party shall require Entrusted Party to maintain obligations equivalent to the confidentiality obligations of Receiving Party hereunder, and shall be liable for any damage caused to Disclosing Party due to a breach of the Agreement by Entrusted Party.
In the event that Receiving Party is requested to disclose Confidential Information by courts, competent authorities or other administrative agencies, Receiving Party shall, prior to the disclosure, notify Disclosing Party in writing of such necessary matters as the contents of the disclosure and the recipient of the information; provided, however, if such prior notice is prohibited by laws etc., Receiving Party shall promptly notify Disclosing Party after disclosure.

Article 4 (Limitation of Copying, etc.)
Without prior written approval of Disclosing Party, Receiving Party shall not copy or otherwise reproduce the whole or part of Confidential Information.
Copies and other reproduction of Confidential Information shall be handled in the same manner as the Confidential Information itself.

Article 6 (Ownership of Confidential Information and No Warranty)
All Confidential Information shall belong to Disclosing Party, and unless otherwise entered into a separate written agreement between the parties, a disclosure of Confidential Information from Disclosing Party to Receiving Party shall in no way mean, whether expressed or implied, the assignment or granting of license to Receiving Party of any rights including the patent right, utility model right, design right, trademark right, copyright or any other intellectual property rights with regard to Confidential Information of Disclosing Party (hereinafter referred to as “Intellectual Property Rights”), and Disclosing Party shall reserve the Intellectual Property Rights.
All of the information disclosed by the Disclosing Party shall be provided as is, and Disclosing Party shall not warrant, whether expressed or implied, that Confidential Information reflects the fact accurately and Confidential Information does not infringe Intellectual Property Rights and any other rights of a third party.

Article 7 (Termination)
If Receiving Party breaches any provision of the Agreement, and such breach is not cured despite the notice of Disclosing Party specifying the considerable period, Disclosing Party may terminate the whole or part of the Agreement, provided that this does not apply if the breach is minor in light of this Agreement and the social rules of business, or if the breach is due to a reason attributable to the Disclosing Party. In such case, Disclosing Party does not lose its right to demand for damages against Receiving Party.

Article 9 (Term of Agreement)
The Agreement shall be effective for *** (**) years from  ***, 2020.  However, technical, commercial or any other information disclosed in connection with the Study by Disclosing Party to Receiving Party prior to the effective date of the Agreement shall also be treated as Confidential Information hereunder.  The provisions of Article 3 paragraph 1, Article 3 paragraph 2, Article 5, Article 6, this Article 9 paragraph 1, Articles 11 through 15 shall survive and effect after expiration of the Agreement.
ThoughtSpot and YAMATO shall agree in writing in the event of termination of the Agreement within the term thereof specified in the preceding paragraph.

Article 11 (Return of Confidential Information, etc.)
When requested by Disclosing Party to return Confidential Information or the Agreement is terminated for any reason whatsoever, Receiving Party shall stop the use of any and all Confidential Information (including its copies, etc.) held by Receiving Party or Entrusted Party and according to the instructions of Disclosing Party, return Confidential Information to Disclosing Party or dispose of it within the period specified by Disclosing Party.  Confidential Information kept electronically or in any other intangible formats shall also be erased completely.

Article 14 (Governing Law)
The Agreement shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of Japan.

All of the information disclosed by the Disclosing Party shall be provided as is, and Disclosing Party shall not warrant, whether expressed or implied, that Confidential Information reflects the fact accurately and Confidential Information does not infringe Intellectual Property Rights and any other rights of a third party.

Confidential Information kept electronically or in any other intangible formats shall also be erased completely.

1.                Definition.  “Confidential Information” means all information disclosed by either party, directly or indirectly, both specifically related to the Purpose, as well as all other proprietary and/or non-public information related to the past, present and future business activities of that party, its subsidiaries and affiliates or their respective employees or third party contractors, including, but not limited to, any information relating to trade secrets, strategic and other plans, pricing, methods, methodologies, processes, financial data, lists, inventions, donor or sponsorship-related information, apparatus, statistics, programs, research, development, information technology, network designs, usage data, the plans and specifications of any product or service that is designed or modified for the party to which it pertains, the terms and existence of this Agreement or related information, and any and all past, present and future agreements and/or business arrangements that have been, are, or are anticipated to be entered into by the parties.  This Agreement applies to any Confidential Information disclosed to either party prior to or as of the parties’ execution of this Agreement.

Obligations. Each party agrees to regard and preserve as confidential, all Confidential Information of the other party. In maintaining the confidentiality of Confidential Information hereunder, each party agrees that it shall not disclose or make available to any person, firm or enterprise, reproduce or transmit, or use for its own benefit or the benefit of others, any such Confidential Information. Each party shall only use the Confidential Information in order to perform its services to the other party. Each party agrees that its use of the Confidential Information shall be limited to its employees only on a “need to know” basis.

Return of Confidential Information. At any time upon the request of the disclosing party, and in the event of termination of this Agreement, the receiving party shall return, or destroy if so directed by the disclosing party, all Confidential Information of the disclosing party, including all copies thereof and notes and other materials incorporating such Confidential Information, whether in physical or electronic form. The term of this Agreement will be three (3) months from the date of the last signature hereto.

Indemnification. In addition to its other obligations hereunder, the receiving party will defend, indemnify and hold harmless the disclosing party, its subsidiaries and affiliates and their respective successors, assigns, officers, directors and employees from damage, loss, liability, costs and expenses of any kind (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) from a negligent breach of the receiving party’s confidentiality obligations regarding any disclosed information hereunder.

Governing law; Arbitration. This Agreement shall be governed by the substantive law of the State of California. Unless otherwise agreed by the parties hereto, any controversy or claim arising out of or relating to this Agreement which remains unresolved after negotiation shall be settled by binding arbitration before the American Arbitration Association, according to its rules. The arbitration shall be conducted in the vicinity of Los Angeles, California and shall be conducted in the English language. Judgment upon the award rendered by the arbitrator(s) may be entered in any court having jurisdiction thereof.

Obligations. Each party agrees to regard and preserve as confidential, all Confidential Information of the other party. In maintaining the confidentiality of Confidential Information hereunder, each party agrees that it shall not disclose or make available to any person, firm or enterprise, reproduce or transmit, or use for its own benefit or the benefit of others, any such Confidential Information. Each party shall only use the Confidential Information in order to perform its services to the other party. Each party agrees that its use of the Confidential Information shall be limited to its employees only on a “need to know” basis.

Unless otherwise agreed by the parties hereto, any controversy or claim arising out of or relating to this Agreement which remains unresolved after negotiation shall be settled by binding arbitration before the American Arbitration Association, according to its rules.  The arbitration shall be conducted in the vicinity of Los Angeles, California and shall be conducted in the English language. 6.        Indemnification.  In addition to its other obligations hereunder, the receiving party will defend, indemnify and hold harmless the disclosing party, its subsidiaries and affiliates and their respective successors, assigns, officers, directors and employees from damage, loss, liability, costs and expenses of any kind (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) from a negligent breach of the receiving party’s confidentiality obligations regarding any disclosed information hereunder.

Return of Confidential Information. At any time upon the request of the disclosing party, and in the event of termination of this Agreement, the receiving party shall return, or destroy if so directed by the disclosing party, all Confidential Information of the disclosing party, including all copies thereof and notes and other materials incorporating such Confidential Information, whether in physical or electronic form. The term of this Agreement will be three (3) months from the date of the last signature hereto.

Obligations of Confidentiality.  The Receiving Party agrees:
to hold the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information in confidence and to take reasonable precautions to protect such Confidential Information (including, without limitation, all precautions the Receiving Party employs with respect to its own confidential materials of a similar nature), 
that it shall disclose the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information only to those of its (and its affiliated entities’) officers, directors, agents, employees, contractors, consultants and financial and legal advisors (collectively “Representatives”) who have a need to know such Confidential Information in connection with the Receiving Party’s evaluation of the Project and not to divulge any such Confidential Information or any information derived therefrom to any third person, 
not to make any use whatsoever at any time of such Confidential Information except to evaluate internally its relationship with the Disclosing Party, 
not to create derivative works of or reverse engineer any such Confidential Information, 
to ensure that its Representatives who have access to the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information have signed confidentiality agreements, or are otherwise bound by confidentiality obligations, at least as restrictive as those contained herein prior to any disclosure of such Confidential Information to such Representatives, 
not to export or re-export (except in compliance with applicable export control laws or regulations) any such Confidential Information, and 
it shall be responsible for compliance with this Agreement its Representatives and affiliated entities to which it discloses the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information.

Exclusions.  Without granting any right or license, the Disclosing Party agrees that the foregoing shall not apply to any information that the Receiving Party can document:
 is or becomes (through no improper action or inaction by the Receiving Party or any of its Representatives) generally available to the public, or 
was rightfully in its possession or known by it without confidentiality restriction prior to receipt from the Disclosing Party, or 
was rightfully disclosed to it by a third party without confidentiality restriction, or 
was independently developed without use of any Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party.

No Grant of Right.  Nothing in this Agreement is intended to grant any rights in or to the other party’s Confidential Information, except as expressly set forth herein. The Receiving Party understands that nothing herein (i) requires the disclosure of any Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party or (ii) requires the Disclosing Party to proceed with any transaction or relationship.

No Representations or Warranties.  Each party understands and acknowledges that the Confidential Information is being provided on an “as is” basis, without any representation or warranty, express or implied, as to the accuracy or completeness of the Confidential Information on the part of the Disclosing Party.
Governing Law.  This Agreement shall be governed by the laws of the State of New York without regard to the conflicts of law provisions thereof.

Remedies.  The Receiving Party acknowledges and agrees that due to the unique nature of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information, there can be no adequate remedy at law for any breach of its obligations hereunder, which breach may result in irreparable harm to the Disclosing Party and, therefore, that upon any such breach or any threat thereof, the Disclosing Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive relief and appropriate equitable relief (without the requirement of posting a bond) in addition to whatever remedies it might have at law.

Term and Termination.  This Agreement commences on the Effective Date and shall continue for five (5) years or until terminated by either party upon thirty (30) days’ prior written notice to the other party’s legal department at the address set forth herein.  Notwithstanding any termination, the rights and obligations herein relating to Confidential Information disclosed prior to termination will survive any termination.

Definition of Confidential Information. “Confidential Information” means all information disclosed by one party (the “Disclosing Party”) to the other (the “Receiving Party”), including, but not limited to, that which relates to patents, patent applications, research, product plans, products, developments, inventions, processes, designs, drawings, engineering, formulae, markets, software (including source and object code), hardware configuration, computer programs, algorithms, business plans, agreements with third parties, services, customers, marketing or finances, whether in oral, written, graphic or electronic form, which would, under the circumstances, appear to a reasonable person to be confidential or proprietary, or is designated as confidential or proprietary.

Purpose. The Company and Counterparty wish to explore a possible business opportunity of mutual interest (the “Relationship”). In connection with the Relationship, each party has disclosed and/or may disclose its Confidential Information (as defined below) to the other. This Agreement is intended to allow the parties to discuss and evaluate the Relationship while protecting each party’s Confidential Information (as defined below) against unauthorized use or disclosure.

Nondisclosure of Confidential Information
(a) Use. The Company and Counterparty each agree not to use any Confidential Information for any purpose other than for the Purpose in Section 1 and to maintain all Confidential Information in trust and confidence. Each party may only disclose or permit disclosure of any Confidential Information to their directors, officers, and employees (“Representatives”) who are reasonably required to have the information with regards to the Relationship, and are bound by the confidentiality obligations substantially similar to these. Each party agrees that it will take all reasonable precautions to prevent the disclosure or use of Confidential Information other than as authorized in this Agreement. Those precautions must be at least as effective as those taken by the Receiving Party to protect its own Confidential Information of a similar nature or those that would be taken by a reasonable person in the position of the Receiving Party, whichever are more effective. Each party agrees to promptly notify the other in writing of any actual or suspected misuse, misappropriation or unauthorized disclosure of Confidential Information. The Receiving Party will be liable for any violations of this Agreement by its Representatives to the same extent that it would have been had it violated this Agreement itself.
(c) Disclosure. Notwithstanding Section 3(a), Confidential Information may be disclosed (i) with the prior written approval of the Disclosing Party; or (ii) an order or requirement of a court,arbiter or governmental body (each, an “Order”) provided that the Receiving Party shall provide prompt notice of the Order to the Disclosing Party prior to disclosure and reasonably assists in obtaining a protective order (if legally permissible). In the event there is no protective order obtained, the Receiving Party shall furnish only that portion of the Confidential Information that is required by the Order and will use commercially reasonable efforts to ensure that confidential treatment is afforded to the disclosed portion.

(b) Exceptions. Notwithstanding the above, Confidential Information will not include information that: (i) was in the public domain at the time it was disclosed or entered the public domain through no fault of the Receiving Party or its Representatives; (ii) was already known, or becomes known, to the Receiving Party or its Representatives without restriction, as the result of disclosure by a third party without breaching its confidential obligations; or (iii) was independently developed by the Receiving Party or its Representatives without any use of or reference to the Confidential Information, as demonstrated by documentary evidence at the time of such independent development.

Ownership of Materials/No Warranty

Disclosing Party retains all rights, title and interest to its Confidential Information.  No license under any trademark, patent or copyright, or application for same which are now or thereafter may be obtained by Disclosing Party is either granted or implied by the disclosure of Confidential Information.  Confidential Information is provided “as is” with all faults.  In no event shall Disclosing Party be liable for the accuracy or completeness of the Confidential Information.

No Rights Granted and No Warranty. Nothing in this Agreement will be construed as granting any rights under any patent, copyright or other intellectual property right of either party, nor will this Agreement grant either party any rights in or to the other party’s Confidential Information other than the limited right to review such Confidential Information solely for the purpose of determining whether to enter into the Relationship. The Receiving Party acknowledges that the Confidential Information is provided as-is and it has not relied on, and will not be relying on the accuracy of any Confidential Information. The Disclosing Party shall not have any liability to the Receiving Party relating to or resulting from the use of any Confidential Information or any inaccuracies or errors.

Governing Law and Venue. This Agreement will be governed by the laws of the State of California without giving effect to principles of conflicts of law. The parties agree that any action in relation to this Agreement, whether under federal or state law, will be brought in Santa Clara County, California.

Remedies. The Company and Counterparty each agree that the obligations in this Agreement are necessary and reasonable in order to protect the Disclosing Party. The Company and Counterparty each expressly agree that monetary damages may be inadequate to compensate the Disclosing Party for any breach of this Agreement. Accordingly, the Company and Counterparty each agree and acknowledge that any such violation or threatened violation will cause irreparable harm to the Disclosing Party and the Disclosing Party will be entitled to seek injunctive relief against the threatened breach of this Agreement or the continuation of any such breach by the Receiving Party, without the necessity of proving actual damages, in addition to any other remedies available.

Return or Destroy. All the Confidential Information within any copies and records, will be
promptly returned or destroyed by the Receiving Party, at the Disclosing Party’s discretion and
upon its written request (including any written notice of termination of the Relationship by either
party). Notwithstanding anything to the contrary, the Receiving Party will not be obligated to erase
Confidential Information contained in an archived computer system backup made in accordance
with reasonable disaster recovery procedures, provided that such archived copy will remain subject
to these obligations.

Term. The foregoing commitments of the Receiving Party shall survive any termination of
the Relationship between the parties, and will continue to the later of (a) 5 years following the date
of this Agreement or (b) 3 years from the date on which Confidential Information is last disclosed,
provided that information labeled as trade secret will be protected indefinitely in accordance with
this Agreement so long as it remain as trade secret under applicable law.

Confidentiality

Receiving Party will use the Confidential Information solely in furtherance of the actual or potential business relationship between the parties.  Receiving Party shall not use the Confidential Information in any way that is directly or indirectly detrimental to Disclosing Party or its subsidiaries or affiliates, and shall not disclose the Confidential Information to any unauthorized third party.  Receiving Party shall ensure that access to Confidential Information is granted only to those of its employees or agents (“Representatives”) who have a demonstrated need to know such information in order to carry out the business purpose of this Agreement.  Prior to disclosing any Confidential Information to such Representatives, Receiving Party shall inform them of the confidential nature of the information and their obligation to refrain from disclosure of the Confidential Information.  Receiving Party and its Representatives will take all reasonable measures to maintain the confidentiality of the Confidential Information, but in no event less than the measures it uses for its own information of similar type.  Receiving Party and its Representatives shall not disclose to any person including, without limitation, any corporation, sovereign, partnership, limited liability company, entity or individual (i) the fact that any investigations, discussions or negotiations are taking place concerning the actual or potential business relationship between the parties, (ii) that it has requested or received Confidential Information, or (iii) any of the terms, conditions or any other fact about the actual or potential business relationship.  Receiving Party and its Representatives will immediately notify Disclosing Party of any use or disclosure of the Confidential Information that is not authorized by this Agreement.  Receiving Party and its Representatives will use its best efforts to assist Disclosing Party in remedying any such unauthorized use or disclosure of the Confidential Information.

The obligations contained in this Section 2 will not apply to the extent that Receiving Party can demonstrate that the Confidential Information: (a) was part of the public domain at the time of disclosure or properly became part of the public domain, by publication or otherwise; (b) was rightfully acquired by Receiving Party prior to disclosure by Disclosing Party; (c) was independently developed by Receiving Party or its Representatives without reference to the Confidential Information; or (d) is required to be disclosed by a government agency or by a proper court of competent jurisdiction; provided, however, that Receiving Party and its Representatives shall provide Disclosing Party prompt prior written notice of such requirement, shall consult with and assist Disclosing Party in obtaining a protective order prior to such disclosure, and shall only disclose the portion of Confidential Information which it has been advised by written opinion of counsel is legally required to be disclosed and shall use its best efforts to obtain assurance that confidential treatment will be accorded such information if the protective order is not obtained or if Disclosing Party waives disclosure of such information.

Ownership of Materials/No Warranty

Disclosing Party retains all rights, title and interest to its Confidential Information.  No license under any trademark, patent or copyright, or application for same which are now or thereafter may be obtained by Disclosing Party is either granted or implied by the disclosure of Confidential Information.  Confidential Information is provided “as is” with all faults.  In no event shall Disclosing Party be liable for the accuracy or completeness of the Confidential Information.

Return of Confidential Information

Upon written request of Disclosing Party, Receiving Party and its Representatives shall promptly return to Disclosing Party all copies of Confidential Information in its possession including, without limitation, all copies of any analyses, compilations, studies or other documents prepared by Receiving Party or its Representatives containing or reflecting any Confidential Information.  Receiving party shall certify in writing that it and its Representatives have returned all such information to Disclosing Party.

Term

This Agreement shall terminate two (2) years from the Effective Date.  Receiving Party’s obligations with respect to confidentiality shall expire after two (2) years from the date of disclosure. In case of Company, the obligation of confidentiality shall survive in perpetuity in respect of Confidential Information of any of Wipro’s customer.

Definitions.  In addition to the terms defined elsewhere in this Agreement, the 
following terms shall have the meanings set forth below:

	a.	“Confidential Information” shall mean any information or material, whether in written, oral, magnetic, electronic, photographic, optical, matter, or other form, which has been, or on or after the date hereof will be, furnished or disclosed by a Party, its affiliates or any of its Related Parties and which has been designated as being confidential or proprietary, or which is otherwise disclosed in such a manner or is of such a character as would put a reasonable person on notice as to the confidential and proprietary nature of such information or material, including, but not limited to, all information and material surrounding the Limited Purpose, any information and material pertaining to or regarding the business, financial condition, sales, marketing, agreements, financial information, pricing, strategies, plans, customers, suppliers, timing and planning schedules, properties, or operations of such Party (including such information visually available to the Recipient at the Discloser’s premises), and including without limitation all technical and non-technical information and material of any nature whatsoever and all, trade secrets, inventions, Technology, formulae, inventions, technical data, know-how, information, derivative works, derivatives, methodologies, concepts, techniques, discoveries, software, software functionality and any related source code or object code, processes, drawings, designs, product descriptions, program descriptions, layouts, renderings, samples, parts, components, systems, vehicles, models, prototypes, procedures, standards, research and development, plans, or specifications relating thereto.

	b.	“Discloser” shall mean the Party disclosing Confidential Information.

	c.	“Recipient” shall mean the Party receiving Confidential Information.

	d.	“Related Party” or “Related Parties” shall mean the affiliates, members, directors, officers, employees, independent contractors, attorneys, accountants, advisors, consultants, or other agents and representatives of a Party, as the case may be and context requires.

	e.	“Technology” shall mean any development, property, information, documentation, material and/or invention developed either solely or jointly with others as a result of use by one Party and/or its Related Party of the Confidential Information of the other Party or of the other Party’s facilities, equipment, material, supplies or premises (whether owned, leased or contracted for).  In addition, Technology shall mean any development, property, information, documentation, material and/or invention developed either solely or jointly with others as a result of use by a Party and/or its Related Party of its own Confidential Information and/or facilities, equipment, material, supplies or premises (whether owned, leased or contracted for).

Ownership.  

	a.	As between the Parties, all Confidential Information of the Discloser is and shall remain the sole and exclusive property of the Discloser. Termination. ThoughtSpot may terminate a Transaction Document for convenience upon fourteen (14) days’ prior notice to Participant. Either party may immediately terminate a Transaction Document in the event that (i) the other party defaults in a material obligation under these Program Terms and fails to cure such default after thirty (30) days written notice unless the terminating party in its reasonable judgment concludes that such breach cannot be, or is not reasonably expected to be, cured; (ii) the other party becomes insolvent, makes a general assignment for the benefit of creditors or becomes subject to any proceeding under any bankruptcy or insolvency laws; and (iii) immediately without prior notice and without further liability if the terminating party reasonably believes that the non-terminating party has engaged in any illegal, immoral, or unethical conduct during the performance of these Program Terms or the Agreement.  Upon termination of the Agreement and/or a Transaction Document, the licenses granted pursuant to Article I Section 7 above shall automatically terminate, and Subcontractor shall cease all use of the Project Materials and destroy or delete all reasonably accessible copies in its possession or control. Upon termination of a Transaction Document for any reason, Prime shall pay to Subcontractor unpaid fees for Services provided, work performed, and expenses incurred by Subcontractor prior to the termination date, subject to the other terms and conditions of the Transaction Document and this Section 2; and Subcontractor shall provide to Prime the Newly-Created Service Documentation and necessary Pre-Existing Service Documentation created for the Subcontractor Services until the date of termination. Disclosing Party and all copies of the Confidential Information not so returned are to be destroyed by the Receiving Party, along with all copies of any analysis, compilations, studies, or other documents prepared by the Receiving Party containing, reflecting, or based upon any Confidential Information. Definitions

The following words and expressions shall bear the following meanings unless the context otherwise requires:

"Confidential Information" means any and/or all information (including information of a commercial, technical, legal or financial nature) that has been or is hereafter provided, in writing, electronically or in any other tangible form and marked ‘confidential’ or the like or expressed to be disclosed as confidential information or provided under circumstances reasonably indicating their confidentiality, to the Receiving Party or its Representatives by or on behalf of the Disclosing Party or any of its Associates, including by their respective Representatives, in the course of, for the purpose of and/or in relation to the Project; which contains, amongst other matters, trade secrets, know-how, show-how, patents research, development or technical information, confidential and/or proprietary product or information, any information or matter comprising or containing part of the intellectual property rights of the Disclosing Party or any other person, business plans, operations or systems, financial and trading positions, details of customers, suppliers, debtors or creditors, information relating to the officers, directors or employees of the Disclosing Party and/or any of its Associates, marketing information, brochures,  rates and rate tables, and/or contracts of any nature. 

“person” includes individual, firm, corporation, association, trust or entity, incorporated or unincorporated.

“Representative” in relation to any party means any director, officer, employee, servant, agent, consultant, advisor (financial, legal or otherwise), auditor or insurer of that party and any of its Associates, and “Representatives” means any two or more of them.

Return of Confidential Information

All Confidential Information in tangible form disclosed by the Disclosing Party to the Receiving Party (including all copies or reproductions thereof in any media and all documents into which any of the Confidential Information has been incorporated) will be returned and delivered up to the Disclosing Party or destroyed by the Receiving Party, immediately upon request by the Disclosing Party, save for such necessary copies retained by the Receiving Party and/or any of its Associates for its file and/or audit, legal or regulatory purposes or compliance with any award, order or legal requirement (including, without limitation, the rules or regulations of any governmental, statutory or regulatory body including without limitation, any relevant stock exchange).

Remedies

5.1	The Receiving Party agrees and acknowledges that money damages are not a sufficient remedy for any breach of this Agreement by the Receiving Party and that the Disclosing Party shall be entitled to specific performance or injunctive relief (as appropriate) as a remedy for any breach or threatened breach thereof, in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity.

5.3	No failure or delay by the Disclosing Party in exercising any right, power or privilege under this Agreement shall operate as a waiver thereof nor shall any single or partial exercise thereof preclude any further exercise thereof or the exercise of any right, power or privilege hereunder or otherwise.

No Representation or Warranty

Accordingly, the Receiving Party acknowledges that the Disclosing Party accepts no liability or responsibility whatsoever and howsoever arising in connection with the Confidential Information (including but not limited to any errors or omissions in the Confidential Information). This Agreement shall create no obligation whatsoever on the Disclosing Party to disclose any Confidential Information, or any particular kind or quantity of thereof.

The Receiving Party shall, in the execution of any agreements relating to the Project, acknowledge that the Receiving Party has not relied on, or been induced by any representation or warranty in the Confidential Information to enter into the agreements, except where expressly specified therein.

Governing Law & Jurisdiction

This Agreement shall be governed and construed in all respects in accordance with the laws of Singapore and the Parties each irrevocably submits to the non-exclusive jurisdiction of the Singapore courts.

Scope of Confidential Information.  
“Confidential Information” means, subject to the exceptions set forth in Section 1.2 hereof, any information or data, regardless of whether it is in tangible form, that is disclosed or otherwise made available by a party hereto (the “Disclosing Party”) to the other party hereto (the “Receiving Party”) and that (a) the Disclosing Party has marked or identified as confidential or proprietary, or (b) the Disclosing Party identifies as confidential in writing within 30 days of disclosure to the Receiving Party; provided, however, that reports and/or information related to or regarding the Disclosing Party’s business plans, business methodologies, strategies, technology, specifications, development plans, bill of materials, pricing, supply chain, sourcing, customers, prospective customers, partners, suppliers, billing records, and products or services shall be deemed Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party even if not so marked or identified, unless such information is the subject of any of the exceptions set forth in Section 1.2 hereof. The Counter Party will not disclose any trade secret of SharkNinja without SharkNinja’s prior written consent.
“Confidential Information” shall not include any information that: (a) is or becomes available to the public (other than as a result of disclosure by Receiving Party or its representatives prohibited by this Agreement); (b) is made available to Receiving Party by a third party who is lawfully in possession of such information, and who is not in violation of any confidentiality obligation in favor of Disclosing Party; or (c) the Receiving Party can show by written record was in available to or in possession of Receiving Party (free of any confidentiality obligation in favor of Disclosing Party known to Receiving Party at the time of disclosure or availability) prior to disclosure of such information by Disclosing Party to Receiving Party, provided that the Receiving Party must promptly notify the Disclosing Party of any prior knowledge in the manner provided in Section 2.4 below.

Certain Rights and Limitations.
All Confidential Information shall remain the property of Disclosing Party.  The provision of Confidential Information hereunder shall not transfer any right, title or interest in such information to Receiving Party.  Disclosing Party does not grant Receiving Party any express or implied right to or under Disclosing Party’s or another party’s patents, copyrights, trademarks, trade secret information or other proprietary rights.

Remedies.  Receiving Party acknowledges that a breach by it of any of the terms of this Agreement would cause irreparable harm to the Disclosing Party for which Disclosing Party could not be adequately compensated by money damages.  Accordingly, Receiving Party agrees that, in addition to all other remedies available to Disclosing Party in an action at law, in the event of any breach or threatened breach by the Receiving Party of the terms of this Agreement, the Disclosing Party shall, without the necessity of proving actual damages or posting any bond or other security, be entitled to temporary and permanent injunctive relief, including, but not limited to, specific performance of the terms of this Agreement.

Termination.  
The term of this Agreement shall commence on the Effective Date and shall expire two (2) years from the Effective Date, provided that SharkNinja may terminate this Agreement at any time by providing written notice to Recipient. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, each Party’s rights and obligations under this Agreement shall survive the expiration or termination of this Agreement for a period of three (3) years even after the return or destruction of Confidential Information by the Recipient provided that, with respect to any Confidential Information that is a trade secret, the rights and obligations hereunder shall survive with respect to such Confidential Information for so long as such Confidential Information remains a trade secret.. 
Upon the earlier of (a) the termination of this Agreement, (b) Disclosing Party’s written request or (c) such time as the Receiving Party no longer requires the Confidential Information for the Permitted Purpose, Receiving Party agrees to promptly return to Disclosing Party or destroy all Confidential Information and any Tangible Embodiments that are in the possession of Receiving Party and to certify the return or destruction of all such Confidential Information and embodiments.
Warranty.  NO WARRANTY IS MADE BY EITHER PARTY UNDER THIS AGREEMENT.  ANY INFORMATION EXCHANGED UNDER THIS AGREEMENT IS PROVIDED “AS IS.”

Confidential Information.  As used in this Agreement, the term “Confidential Information” shall mean any confidential, non-public or proprietary information disclosed by the Disclosing Party to the Receiving Party, whether transmitted in oral, written or graphical form or obtained by observation or otherwise during office or facility visits, including, without limitation, the Disclosing Party’s business or operating plans; intellectual property (including trade secrets, trademarks, copyrights, plans, research and development, processes, menus, recipes, meal preparation techniques, formulae, reports, protocols, know-how, business methods strategies, and technology); operating methods and processes; tax information; financial condition and results of operations; operating and employee policies and manuals; compensation information; products, product development, distribution, and sales; support and marketing plans; customer, supplier and vendor information; pricing and strategies; management structure; and information received from third parties under confidential conditions, together with any analyses, compilations, studies or other documents or records prepared by the Disclosing Party or the Receiving Party or any of its Representatives pertaining to such information.

Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Receiving Party’s obligations hereunder with respect to the Confidential Information shall continue in full force and effect and shall survive termination or expiration of this Agreement, unless it is subject to one or more of the exceptions set forth herein.

Nothing herein shall be construed as representing any commitment by either party to enter into any additional agreement, by implication or otherwise, and neither party shall have any obligation to do so.

No Warranties. The Disclosing Party will have no duty to update any Confidential Information.

Remedies.  The Receiving Party acknowledges that an unauthorized disclosure or use of Confidential Information may result in irreparable harm to the Disclosing Party. This provision does not alter any other remedies available to the Disclosing Party.  The Receiving Party will not raise the defense of an adequate remedy at law.

Definition. “Confidential Information” means any non-public information, whether in tangible, machine readable or electronic form, disclosed by either of the parties to the other, which the Discloser identifies at the time of disclosure as confidential by means of a legend, marking, stamp or other notice conspicuously designating the information to be confidential, or information disclosed orally or visually by either of the parties to the other where the Discloser identifies such information as confidential at the time of disclosure and, within thirty (30) days after such oral or visual disclosure, reduces the subject matter of the disclosure to a tangible or electronic form properly identified in the manner described above and submits it to the Recipient. Covered Entity shall implement security measures to protect e-PHI transmitted to Business Associate from unauthorized access, which may include use of the Transport Layer Security (“TLS”) protocol or other encryption mechanism.
