ARTICLE 3 – OBLIGATION OF SECRECY
3.1        During the Term of this Agreement and for a further period of five (5) years thereafter (except for source code, which must be kept in confidence in perpetuity), the Receiving Party and its Affiliates shall maintain all Confidential Information received from the Disclosing Party in strict confidence and undertake: (i) not to disclose the Confidential Information received from the Disclosing Party to any third party, without receiving formal written approval of the Disclosing Party in advance; (ii) not to use the Confidential Information received from the Disclosing Party for any purpose other than the Scope; (iii) to take all necessary steps to prevent any access by a third party to the Confidential Information  received from the Disclosing Party; (iv) not to use the Confidential Information  in any way detrimental to the interests of the Disclosing Party or so as to obtain any competitive advantage for themselves; and (v) not to file any patent applications disclosing the Confidential Information received.
3.2        The Receiving Party and its Affiliates shall ensure that all Confidential Information received from the Disclosing Party is kept secure, shall restrict access to the Confidential Information on a strict need-to-know basis, and shall take reasonable steps to ensure that its employees, directors, and officers who receive or have access to any Confidential Information are aware of the existence and terms of this Agreement and are bound by terms of secrecy at least to the same extent that the Receiving Party and its Affiliates are bound by this Agreement.
        If the Receiving Party or its Affiliates wish to involve third parties that are part of or are themselves a legal entity other than the Receiving Party, the Disclosing Party shall be consulted prior to any such involvement and their agreement requested.  
3.3        Without the prior written agreement, the Parties nor their Affiliates will disclose to any individual or entity the fact that the Confidential Information has been made available, or that discussions or negotiations are taking place or have taken place concerning the Scope, including the status of any discussions or negotiations with respect to the Scope.
3.4        Without limiting the liability of its employees, directors, and officers, the Receiving Party shall be liable in the case of any breach of the secrecy obligations provided for in this Agreement by any of its employees, directors, or officers.
3.5        The Confidential Information which has been or will be disclosed to the Receiving Party or its Affiliates shall remain the exclusive property of the Disclosing Party.
3.6        The received Confidential Information shall not be mechanically copied or otherwise reproduced by the Receiving Party or its Affiliates without the express written permission of the Disclosing Party, except for such copies that the Parties may require pursuant to this Agreement for internal evaluation purposes on a need-to-know basis.
        All copies shall, on reproduction by the Receiving Party or its Affiliates, contain the same proprietary and confidential notices and legends which appear on the original information, unless expressly authorized otherwise by the Disclosing Party.
3.7	For any sample provided by the Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party shall neither analyze nor reverse-engineer such sample, nor give it to any third party for said purposes, unless following explicit approval, in writing, by the Disclosing Party.
3.8	The Receiving Party and its Affiliates will return to the Disclosing Party immediately, upon its written request, all copies of the Confidential Information.  Further, upon the written request of the Disclosing Party, that portion of the Confidential Information which consists of analyses, compilations, excerpts, forecasts, summaries, studies or other documents and writings prepared by the Receiving Party that are based upon or incorporate any Confidential Information will immediately be destroyed by the Receiving Party and its Affiliates as the case may be.
	If requested by the Disclosing Party, such destruction shall be certified in writing to the Disclosing Party by an authorized representative of the Receiving Party and its Affiliates.  The return and/or destruction of such Confidential Information as provided above shall not relieve the Receiving Party and its Affiliates of other obligations under this Agreement.
3.9	By signing this Agreement, the Receiving Party and its Affiliates also expressly acknowledge having been made aware, and undertake to make all representatives of the Receiving Party and its Affiliates who have received Confidential Information of AB INBEV aware in writing, that (i) the shares of AB INBEV are listed on Euronext Brussels, (ii) that therefore any individual who is in possession of information related to AB INBEV itself or to one of its subsidiaries possesses information which may constitute insider information under applicable laws on the prohibition of insider trading, (iii) that these laws make it a criminal offence for an individual who has an information as an insider to deal on or off a regulated market in shares or other financial instruments whose price would be significantly affected if the insider information were made public and (iv) that similar restrictions and prohibitions apply to insider information on companies other than AB INBEV on which the Receiving Party, or such companies or a third party, would supply information to the Receiving Party or its Affiliates in relation to the Project, to the extent the shares or other financial instruments of such companies are listed on a stock market.

ARTICLE 4 – OWNERSHIP
4.1	All reports and other documentation, models, prototypes, contrivances, structures, and other materials (in tangible or intangible form), including all embodiments and copies of the foregoing, made or prepared by or on behalf of the Receiving Party in relation to any of AB INBEV's Confidential Information (the “Materials”) shall be the property of AB INBEV and shall be delivered on request to AB INBEV by the Receiving Party. Either party (“Discloser”) may at its option make available to the other party (“Recipient”) in the performance of this Agreement information of a confidential or proprietary nature to such party, including information of its affiliates or of a third party (hereinafter referred to as “Confidential Information”).  As used in this Agreement, the Confidential Information shall mean any information or data in oral and/or written form which Recipient knows or has reason to know is Confidential Information and which is disclosed in connection with this Agreement or which Recipient may have access to in connection with this Agreement, including but not limited to business and marketing plans, strategic alliances, cost or pricing data, the identities of customers and prospective customers.  To the extent practicable, Confidential Information shall be clearly identified or labeled as such at the time of disclosure or as promptly thereafter as possible, however, failure to so identify or label such Confidential Information shall not be evidence that such information is not proprietary or protectable.

Confidential Information shall not include any information which (a) was rightfully in the possession of Recipient prior to disclosure by Discloser; (b) was or is independently developed by Recipient without use of the Confidential Information;  (c) is now or hereafter becomes available to the public other than as a result of disclosure by Recipient in violation of this Agreement; or (d) becomes available to Recipient on a non-confidential basis from a source other than Discloser and such source was under no obligation to Discloser to keep such information confidential.

Degree of Care.  Recipient shall maintain the Confidential Information using the same degree of care as it uses to protect its own confidential and proprietary information but in any case using no less than a reasonable degree of care.  In addition, Recipient shall not use the Confidential Information received from Discloser for its own benefit or, except as expressly provided for herein, disclose the Confidential Information to third parties without the prior written consent of an authorized representative of Discloser.  Each party understands that the other party’s Confidential Information may constitute material non-public information under U.S. securities laws and regulations and will not transact in securities of the other party or its affiliates based on the Confidential Information.  In addition, each party agrees to take reasonable measures to ensure that its directors, officers, employees, agents, independent contractors and consultants are aware that such Confidential Information may constitute non-public information under U.S. securities laws and regulations.

Permitted Disclosure.  Recipient agrees to disclose the Confidential Information only to its directors, officers, employees, agents, independent contractors and consultants who have a need to know the Confidential Information as required in furtherance of the objectives of the business relationship between the parties, and with respect to independent contractors and consultants, only those who have agreed to substantially similar non-disclosure obligations as those contained herein.  Notwithstanding the foregoing, CDW may disclose the Confidential Information to its affiliates and their directors, officers, employees and agents who may also have a need to know the Confidential Information in furtherance of the business relationship.  
Limitation On Use.  Recipient shall use the Confidential Information only in connection with the furtherance of the business relationship between the parties, and Recipient shall make no further use, in whole or in part, of any Confidential Information.  However, nothing in this Agreement shall restrict Discloser from using, disclosing, or disseminating its own Confidential Information in any way.

Legal Action Requiring Disclosure.  If Recipient is required by law, rule or regulation, or requested in any judicial or administrative proceeding or by any governmental or regulatory authority, to disclose the Confidential Information, Recipient shall give Discloser prompt notice of such request so that Discloser may seek an appropriate protective order or similar protective measure.  Upon Discloser’s written request Recipient shall, at Discloser’s expense, cooperate with Discloser in seeking such order or similar protective measure.  If Recipient is nonetheless compelled to disclose the Confidential Information, Recipient shall disclose only that portion of the Confidential Information that Recipient is legally required to disclose and, upon Discloser’s request and expense, shall use reasonable efforts to obtain assurances that confidential treatment will be accorded to such Confidential Information to the extent such assurances are available.

Return Or Destruction Of Confidential Information.  Recipient is hereby authorized to make only the number of copies of the Confidential Information necessary to disseminate the Confidential Information to those who are entitled to have access to it, and ensure that all confidentiality notices set forth on the Confidential Information are reproduced in full on such copies.  At the written request of Discloser, Recipient agrees to return or, at Discloser’s sole discretion, destroy all materials in its possession and control, which contain any Confidential Information and shall, at Discloser’s written request, certify in writing to Discloser that all copies (in any form or media) have been destroyed or returned to Discloser.

Injunctive Relief.  Each party acknowledges that unauthorized disclosure or use of the Confidential Information by Recipient may cause irreparable harm and damage to the business of Discloser which may be difficult to ascertain and which may not be adequately compensated by damages at law.  Therefore, each party agrees that, in the event of a breach or threatened breach of the terms of this Agreement, Discloser shall be entitled to seek an injunction prohibiting any unauthorized disclosure or use of its Confidential Information.  Any such injunctive relief request may be in addition to, and not in lieu of, any appropriate monetary damages.

Term of Confidentiality.  Recipient shall maintain the Confidential Information in accordance with this Agreement for a period of five (5) years from the date of disclosure, provided however, to the extent the Confidential Information constitutes a trade secret under law, Recipient agrees to protect such information for so long as it qualifies as a trade secret under applicable law.

Remedies. The parties further agree that in the event of such disclosure or threatened disclosure: (a) the Discloser shall be entitled to seek an injunction without the requirement of posting a bond, to prevent the breach or threatened breach without the necessity of proving irreparable injury or the inadequacy of money damages, in addition to any other remedies available to the disclosing party at law or in equity, and (b) each party hereby acknowledges that such an injunction is may be appropriate and warranted in such case. Unless specifically provided otherwise in this Agreement, remedies arising under this Agreement are cumulative and do not exclude any other remedies available at law or in equity.

Term and Termination. Either party may terminate the Agreement in writing, whereupon Recipient will stop all use of Discloser’s Confidential Information. Regardless of any termination of this Agreement, Recipient must meet its obligations with respect to Confidential Information under this Agreement for five (5) years after receipt of that Confidential Information (except for source code, which must be kept in confidence in perpetuity). Upon written request of the Discloser, Recipient will promptly return to Discloser or destroy (or in the case of electronic data, use commercially reasonable efforts to delete or render practicably inaccessible by Recipient) Confidential Information of Discloser except for: (i) Confidential Information the Recipient is obliged by law to retain; (ii) extracts of, or references to, Confidential Information contained in board or investment committee minutes or papers, due diligence reports or any other materials delivered to the Board in relation to consideration of the Purpose; (iii) any documents or other materials required for internal corporate governance, risk management or audit purposes or for the purposes of insurance or risk management policies or to comply with professional standards which are applicable to its financial or legal advisers provided that any Confidential Information so retained must only be accessed for reasonable and bona fide compliance purposes; or (iv) any Confidential Information which is stored electronically pursuant to an existing routine data back-up exercise on servers or back-up sources so long as it is deleted from local hard drives and no attempt is made to recover it from those servers or back-up sources other than as required by law, provided that any Confidential Information retained is kept confidential in accordance with the terms of this Agreement.

If a Party is found to be in breach of this Agreement (“Defaulting Party”), the Defaulting Party must indemnify the other Party, on demand, against any and all loss, damage, claims and expenses which are suffered or incurred by the Defaulting Party directly or indirectly in respect of any breach by the Defaulting Party of this Agreement or any breach by any related person.
Forthwith on termination or expiry of the Purpose or at one Party’s (“first Party”) first written request, the other (“other Party”) shall (at the first Party’s option) return or destroy (and in that case certify destruction of) the Confidential Information of the first Party (including without limitation all copies in whatever format) except to the extent that the same form part of the permanent records of the other Party which it is bound by law or regulatory requirement to preserve and the provisions of this Agreement shall, notwithstanding its termination, continue to apply to all such retained information.

Definitions.  When used in this Agreement, the following terms shall have the meanings given below:

(a)	“Affiliates” of a person or entity means any other person or entity that directly or indirectly, through one or more intermediaries, controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with, such person or entity.  The term “control” (including the terms “controlled by” and “under common control with”) means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management and policies of a person or entity, whether through the ownership of voting securities, by contract or otherwise.

(b)	“Confidential Information” means (whether disclosed directly or indirectly, in writing, electronically, orally, or by inspection or viewing, or in any other form or medium) all proprietary, non-public information of or relating to the Disclosing Party or any of its Affiliates, including but not limited to, financial information, customer lists, supplier lists, business forecasts, software, sales, merchandising and marketing plans and materials, proprietary technology and products, whether or not subject to registration, patent filing or copyright, and all notes, summaries, reports, analyses, compilations, studies and interpretations of any Confidential Information or incorporating any Confidential Information, whether prepared by or on behalf of the Disclosing Party or the Receiving Party.  Confidential Information shall also include the fact that discussions or negotiations are taking place concerning the Transaction between the Disclosing Party and the Receiving Party, and any of the terms, conditions or other facts with respect to any such Transaction, including the status thereof.

	Notwithstanding the foregoing, Confidential Information does not include information that: (i) was or becomes generally available to the public other than as a result of a disclosure by Receiving Party or its Representatives in violation of this Agreement; (ii) was or becomes available to the Receiving Party from a source other than the Disclosing Party or its Representatives, provided that such source was not known by Receiving Party to be bound by contract, legal or fiduciary obligation of confidentiality to the Disclosing Party; or (iii) the Receiving Party can demonstrate to have independently developed such information without the use of any Confidential Information.

Nondisclosure.  The Receiving Party will keep all Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party confidential and will not, directly or indirectly, disclose the Confidential Information, or permit its disclosure, by its Affiliates or by its or its Affiliates’ respective officers, directors, partners, consultants, employees, agents, advisors, accountants, attorneys, regulators, auditors, lenders, equity owners, or potential lenders or investors (collectively its “Representatives”) in any manner whatsoever in whole or in part except as expressly permitted by this Agreement.  The Receiving Party shall have the right to disclose the Confidential Information to its Representatives only on a “need-to-know” basis and only for the purpose of evaluating the Transaction.  The Representatives shall be bound by obligations of confidentiality to the Receiving Party, or the Receiving Party, prior to disclosing any Confidential Information to its Representatives, shall issue appropriate instructions to its Representatives and obtain all necessary undertakings to assure that its Representatives comply with the confidentiality and use obligations and restrictions contained in this Agreement. The Receiving Party and its Representatives will use the Confidential Information solely in connection with the Transaction. Except as set forth in this paragraph (and in Section 3 below), no other disclosure of Confidential Information is permitted by the Receiving Party.  The Receiving Party agrees to be fully responsible for any breach of the terms of this Agreement by its Representatives.

Required Disclosure.  If the Receiving Party or its Representatives becomes legally required to disclose any Confidential Information, the Receiving Party will give the Disclosing Party prompt notice of such fact (unless notice is prohibited by law in which case such notice shall be provided as promptly as legally permissible) so that the Disclosing Party may, at its sole expense, attempt to obtain a protective order or other appropriate remedy concerning any such disclosure.  The Receiving Party will use reasonable efforts to cooperate with the Disclosing Party in connection with the Disclosing Party’s efforts to obtain any such order or other remedy.  Failing the entry of a protective order or remedy, Receiving Party and its Representatives may disclose that portion of the Confidential Information that it reasonably believes it is compelled to disclose and it will exercise reasonable efforts to obtain assurance that confidential treatment will be afforded to that portion of the Confidential Information that is being disclosed.  Notwithstanding the foregoing, no notice shall be required in connection with any disclosures of Confidential Information made by the Receiving Party or its Representatives pursuant to any regulatory review by any governmental agency or regulatory body that does not specifically reference the Transaction or the Disclosing Party.

Return/Destruction of Confidential Information.  Upon request by the Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party shall, and shall cause its Representatives to, promptly discontinue use of the Confidential Information and shall either return the Confidential Information to the Disclosing Party, or certify as to the destruction of all Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party.  Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Receiving Party and its Representatives may retain the Confidential Information to the extent required by law, regulation, or in accordance with the Receiving Party’s or such Representative’s record keeping policies, and may retain any electronic copies of such Confidential Information created by the Receiving Party’s or such Representative’s archival or backup systems, subject to the continuing obligations of confidentiality and non-use, which shall survive termination of this Agreement.

Remedies.  Receiving Party agrees to indemnify and hold harmless the Disclosing Party from any damage, loss, cost or liability (including legal fees and the cost of enforcing this indemnity) arising out of or resulting from any (a) unauthorized use or disclosure by the Receiving Party or its Representatives of Confidential Information and (b) any breach by the Receiving Party of any material provision of this Agreement.   Receiving Party agrees that a failure to comply with any provision of this Agreement will cause Disclosing Party irreparable harm which could not adequately be compensated by monetary damages, and that Disclosing Party shall be entitled to equitable relief without the requirement to prove damages or post a bond in order to enforce any provision of this Agreement, which right shall be in addition, to, and not in lieu of, any other remedy to which the Disclosing Party is entitled under applicable law.

Term.  The Term of this Agreement will expire upon the earlier of (a) two (2) years from the date hereof, or (b) upon the Parties’ execution of a definitive agreement with respect to the Transaction, except that the obligations of confidentiality and non-use hereunder with regard (i) to Confidential Information of the Disclosing Party that constitute trade secrets of the Disclosing Party under applicable law shall remain in effect for as long as such Confidential Information remains a trade secret under applicable law, and (ii) to backed-up, archived or retained Confidential Information of Disclosing Party hereunder in accordance with Section 4 shall remain in effect for as long as such Confidential Information is backed-up, archived or retained.

Confidential Information. “Confidential Information” means technical, business, personally identifiable, and other information and materials that may be disclosed or otherwise made available by one party (“Discloser”) (whether directly or indirectly by an affiliate) to the other party (whether directly or indirectly to an affiliate) (“Recipient”), in any form, that are:
marked or identified as confidential or proprietary at the time of disclosure; or
provided under circumstances reasonably indicating their confidentiality

Responsibilities Regarding Confidential Information. Recipient will:
hold Discloser’s Confidential Information in confidence and not disclose such Confidential Information to any third party;
not use or copy Discloser’s Confidential Information for any purpose except for the Purpose; and
take reasonable precautions (at least equivalent to those Recipient takes with respect to its own similar information, but no less than a reasonable degree of care) to prevent unauthorized disclosure or use of Discloser’s Confidential Information and will maintain source code in confidence for as long as it is in Recipient’s possession.

Exceptions and Clarifications. 
Recipient’s obligations hereunder will not apply to any Confidential Information to the extent Recipient can show that it: 
is now, or subsequently becomes, generally available through no improper act or omission of Recipient or its Representatives; 
was before receipt from Discloser, or becomes, rightfully known to Recipient without confidentiality restrictions through disclosure from a source other than Discloser that does not owe a duty of confidentiality to Discloser with respect to such Confidential Information; or
is independently developed by Recipient without using or referencing any Confidential Information of Discloser.
Recipient may disclose Discloser’s Confidential Information to the extent required by law or regulation provided that Recipient will: (i) give Discloser reasonable prior written notice before making the disclosure; (ii) provide reasonable assistance to Discloser in any lawful efforts by the Discloser to resist or limit the disclosure of such Confidential Information; and (iii) limit the scope of such disclosure to the minimum required by the law or regulation.
Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, Recipient may use and disclose Residuals for any purpose, including use in the acquisition, development, manufacture, promotion, sale, or maintenance of products and services.  The term “Residuals” means information that is retained in the unaided memories of Recipient’s employees or Representatives who have had authorized access to Discloser’s Confidential Information in connection with this Agreement.  The Recipient shall have no obligation to limit or restrict assignment of such persons or to pay royalties for any work resulting from use of Residuals.

Ownership. As between the parties, all Confidential Information disclosed under this Agreement will remain the property of the Discloser. No license or right under any intellectual property right, nor any conveyance of intellectual property, is effected under this Agreement or by any disclosure of Confidential Information except as expressly stated in this Agreement.

Warranty. Discloser warrants that it has the right to disclose Confidential Information. EXCEPT AS STATED HEREIN, THE CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION IS PROVIDED “AS IS, WITH ALL FAULTS” AND WITH NO OTHER WARRANTIES, EXPRESS OR IMPLIED.

Remedies.  The parties agree that the Recipient’s disclosure of Confidential Information except as provided herein may result in irreparable injury for which a remedy in money damages would be inadequate. The parties further agree that in the event of such disclosure or threatened disclosure: (a) the Discloser shall be entitled to seek an injunction without the requirement of posting a bond, to prevent the breach or threatened breach without the necessity of proving irreparable injury or the inadequacy of money damages, in addition to any other remedies available to the disclosing party at law or in equity, and (b) each party hereby acknowledges that such an injunction is appropriate and warranted in such case. Unless specifically provided otherwise in this Agreement, remedies arising under this Agreement are cumulative and do not exclude any other remedies available at law or in equity.

Term and Termination. Either party may terminate the Agreement in writing, whereupon Recipient will stop all use of Discloser’s Confidential Information. Regardless of any termination of this Agreement, Recipient must meet its obligations with respect to Confidential Information under this Agreement for five (5) years after receipt of that Confidential Information (except for source code, which must be kept in confidence in perpetuity). Upon written request of the Discloser, Recipient will promptly return to Discloser or destroy (or in the case of electronic data, use commercially reasonable efforts to delete or render practicably inaccessible by Recipient) Confidential Information of Discloser.

WHEREAS  The Parties will disclose or exchange certain information or data that is confidential by its nature including without limitation technical, commercial, financial, marketing, operational or strategic information related to the business of a Party, on any verbal, visual or written medium, whether it is marked confidential or restricted or not (“Confidential Information”), that is communicated by a Party (the “Disclosing Party”) to the other Party (the “Recipient”) during the Term, and that the Disclosing Party desires for the Recipient to keep confidential and use only in connection with the business purpose for which it has been disclosed which is to assist CN in xxxxxxxxxxxxx (the “Purpose”).

Term

This Agreement shall take effect on the Effective Date and shall continue in effect for two (2) years (the “Term”), with the confidentiality obligations herein surviving for three (3) years after the early termination of the Agreement or, if no such early termination occurs, after the expiration of the Term. Termination or expiration shall not affect any claim the Disclosing Party may have for a breach of this Agreement by the Recipient or anyone to whom the Recipient has disclosed pursuant to Article 4 below.

Confidential Discussions

The fact that the Parties are engaging in discussions with each other regarding the Confidential Information or the Purpose, and the fact of either Party's involvement or interest in the Confidential Information or the Purpose, are part of the Confidential Information and are subject to the confidentiality obligations set out in Article 4 below.

No Restrictions

Notwithstanding any other provision of this Agreement, no restrictions apply to any information that:

is independently developed or acquired by the Recipient without breach of this Agreement or any other confidentiality agreement; or
at the time of disclosure, was known to the Recipient on a non-confidential basis; or
is lawfully received from another source without breach of the Agreement or any other confidentiality agreement; or
is or becomes a matter of public knowledge without breach of this Agreement or any other confidentiality agreement; or
is disclosed under operation of law, except that Recipient shall notify the Disclosing Party of any disclosure request, disclose only such Confidential Information as is legally required and shall use reasonable efforts to ensure the continued confidential treatment of any Confidential Information that is disclosed.

Ownership of Confidential Information

The Confidential Information and all physical copies of it shall at all times remain the property of the Disclosing Party who retains all right, title and interest in its Confidential Information and in no event shall Recipient acquire any rights with respect to same. The Recipient shall, upon the request of the Disclosing Party, promptly return all copies of the Confidential Information.

In the RFP documents and during the RFP process, certain information that CBC/Radio-Canadaa Party (“Disclosing Party”) deems proprietary and confidential will be disclosed to the other Party (“Receiving Party,”), orally, in written or in other form.  Unless specifically identified otherwise herein or with the information transmitted, all information disclosed by CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party in the RFP and during the RFP process shall be deemed proprietary and confidential (“Confidential Information”).  The Confidential Information may include without limitation, information and material of CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party such as formulae, patterns, compilations, programs, designs, concepts, devices, methods, techniques and processes, financial information, business plans, business strategies, marketing plans, cost information, information about employees, process descriptions, descriptions of technical know-how, engineering and technical specifications and documentation.

The Parties agree that the provision of Confidential Information to the Receiving Party is not in any way intended to be and shall not be deemed to be a public disclosure, public use, or otherwise a publication of that information by CBC/Radio-Canada.the Disclosing Party.  The Confidential Information disclosed by CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party shall be and remains the property of CBC/Radio-Canada.the Disclosing Party.  The Confidential Information will be used by the Receiving Party solely for the purpose of responding to the RFP and evaluating a possible agreement in association with the RFP, and not used in any way directly or indirectly detrimental to CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party. Prevention of Disclosure
The Receiving Party agrees that all Confidential Information received from CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party shall be treated as proprietary and confidential and subject to Section 3 hereunder, the Receiving Party shall not disclose any such Confidential Information to any third party or share such information with any third party, including other proponents in the RFP process, unless the Receiving Party has obtained the prior written consent of the representative of CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party whose name appear in Section 3 below.
The Receiving Party also undertakes to prevent the disclosure of documents or material in written, digital or other form that are prepared by the Receiving Party or its Representatives (as defined hereunder) based on Confidential Information (“Derivative Confidential Information”). Derivative Confidential Information shall be governed by the terms of this Agreement as if it were original Confidential Information supplied by CBC/Radio-Canada.the Disclosing Party.  
The Receiving Party agrees to be responsible for any breach of this Agreement by any Representative (as defined hereunder) to whom the Receiving Party discloses the Confidential Information.

Exceptions to Confidentiality
The Parties hereto agree that Confidential Information shall not be deemed confidential and the Receiving Party shall have no obligation with respect to any such Confidential Information which:
(a)	is or subsequently becomes publicly available or generally known in the industry without the Receiving Party’s breach of any obligation to CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party; or,
(b)	becomes known to the Receiving Party from a source other than CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party other than by the breach of an obligation of confidentiality owed to CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party; or,
(c)	the Receiving Party can demonstrate is independently developed by the Receiving Party with no use or access to the Confidential Information; or,
(d)	is required to be disclosed by the Receiving Party pursuant to subpoena or court or administrative order, provided that the Receiving Party shall take reasonable steps to give CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party sufficient prior notice to permit CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party to contest or restrict such disclosure.

Return of Confidential Information
Should the Receiving Party decide not to submit a response, it shall forthwith upon reaching such decision return to CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party or destroy all documents relating to the RFP and all copies thereof that it may have made.  It shall also remit to CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party a list of any Representatives (except for the Receiving Party’s employees) to whom it may have conveyed any part or the whole of the RFP.  
Should the Receiving Party decide to submit a response, it and any Representatives will return to CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party or destroy and make no further use of all Confidential Information received from CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party upon the earlier of: (i) receipt of a notice from CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party that its response has been rejected or that the RFP process is cancelled; or (ii) a written request by CBC/Radio-Canada.the Disclosing Party.  The Receiving Party and any Representatives shall destroy any and all Derivative Confidential Information upon the earlier of such events. 
Any destruction of Confidential Information or Derivative Confidential Information shall be confirmed in writing to CBC/Radio Canadathe Disclosing Party by an authorized officer of the Receiving Party or the Representatives, as the case may be.

Liability for Damages
The Receiving Party agrees that unauthorized disclosure or use of Confidential Information may cause irreparable harm and significant injury which may be difficult to ascertain.  Accordingly, the Receiving Party agrees that it shall be liable for all damages caused by its own or its Representatives’ disclosure or use of Confidential Information in breach of this Agreement and agrees that CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party shall have the right to seek equitable relief including, without limitation, injunction and specific performance, in the event of any breach of the provisions of this Agreement, in addition to all other remedies available to CBC/Radio-Canada the Disclosing Party at law or in equity.  The Receiving Party agrees to pay all of CBC/Radio-Canada’sthe Disclosing Party’s costs and legal expenses in such litigation if the Receiving Party and/or a Representative, is found to have breached this Agreement.

Representation or Warranty
The Receiving Party acknowledges that neither CBC/Radio-Canadathe Disclosing Party nor any of its employees, consultants or other representatives has made or is making any representation or warranty (express or implied) as to the accuracy or completeness of the Confidential Information.

Survival of Terms and Conditions of Agreement
The foregoing commitments of the Receiving partyParty shall survive the termination of the RFP process and discussions between the Parties, and shall continue for a period terminating five (5) years following the signature date of this Agreement (except for source code, which must be kept in confidence in perpetuity).

NDA Purpose: to facilitate the parties’ business discussions and exchange of information about potential business transactions between Calix and Company related to general business opportunity discussions.
Purpose. Calix and Company wish to explore a business opportunity concerning the Purpose pursuant to which either party (“Discloser”) may disclose its Confidential Information (as defined below) to the other party (“Recipient”). This Agreement is intended to allow the parties to discuss and evaluate the Purpose while protecting each party’s Confidential Information against unauthorized use or disclosure.

Confidential Information. “Confidential Information” means all technical and non-technical information in any form, whether oral, written or other tangible form, that the Discloser designates as being confidential or which, given the nature of the information or the circumstances surrounding disclosure, would reasonably be considered as confidential and/or proprietary, including but not limited to business plans, business concepts, marketing plans, financial information, purchasing requirements, customer lists, price lists, pricing methods, sales plans, forecasts, specifications, trade secrets, know-how, methodologies, drawings, models, research, equipment, algorithms, processes, techniques, ideas, inventions (whether patentable or not), programs, source code, object code, prototype, designs, compositions, data, databases, schematics, product development, and manufacturing plans, and any extracts, summaries and analyses of, or information derived from, the foregoing. Confidential Information also includes the confidential information of a third party which is disclosed under this Agreement. Neither party shall communicate any information to the other in violation of the proprietary rights of any third party. Confidential Information disclosed to the Recipient by Discloser’s subsidiaries and affiliates are covered by this Agreement.

Nondisclosure Obligations. 

(a)  Calix and Company agree to keep in confidence, and will cause their respective Representatives (as defined below) to keep in confidence, all Confidential Information disclosed to them and will use such Confidential Information only for the Purpose. Recipient will use the same standard of care to prevent the disclosure of Confidential Information to any third party that the Recipient uses to protect its own Confidential Information of a similar nature, but in any event not less than a reasonable standard of care. Recipient may disclose Discloser’s Confidential Information to Recipient’s directors, employees, advisors and consultants (“Representatives”) who (i) have a need to know the information in connection with their duties and (ii) are parties to confidentiality agreements with Recipient that protect Discloser’s Confidential Information with terms no less stringent than those in this Agreement. Recipient will be responsible for any breach of this Agreement by its Representatives. Recipient agrees to notify Discloser in writing of any actual or suspected misuse, misappropriation or unauthorized disclosure of Confidential Information of Discloser which may come to Recipient’s attention.
(b)  Without Discloser’s prior written consent, Recipient will not, and will direct its Representatives not to, disclose to any person either the fact that discussion or negotiations are taking place concerning cooperative activities or the status thereof. For purposes of this provision, the term “person” shall be broadly interpreted to include without limitation any corporation, company, partnership, other legal entity and individual.

Return of Materials. Upon termination of discussions, termination of this Agreement or the Discloser’s written request, Recipient and its Representatives shall cease using Discloser’s Confidential Information and shall return or destroy all tangible copies of Discloser’s Confidential Information (including any extracts, summaries and analyses, or information derived therefrom) in Recipient’s (or its Representative’s) possession or control.

Term and Termination. This Agreement will become effective on the Effective Date and will continue until terminated by either party with 30 days prior written notice to the other party. Notwithstanding the termination of this Agreement, each party’s obligations with respect to the other party’s Confidential Information will continue for 5 years after the effective termination date of the Agreementfollowing Recipient’s receipt of that Confidential Information. With respect to Confidential Information that constitutes trade secrets (including but not limited to source code), the restrictions set forth in this Agreement will continue in effect for perpetuity or so long as such information remains a trade secret.

No Representations or Warranties. Each party acknowledges that the other party makes no representations or warranties as to the accuracy or completeness of the Confidential Information. All Confidential Information is delivered “AS IS,” and all representations warranties, express or implied, including fitness for a particular purpose, merchantability, and noninfringement are hereby disclaimed.

Rights and Remedies. The parties agree that any breach or threatened breach of this Agreement would cause irreparable injury to Discloser for which no adequate remedy at law exists; therefore, the parties agree that in addition to all other remedies available to the parties, equitable remedies, including without limitation unilateral injunctive relief and specific performance, are appropriate remedies to redress any breach or threatened breach of this Agreement by Recipient, any of its Representatives, or any other persons directly or indirectly acting for or on behalf of or with Recipient. All rights and remedies hereunder shall be cumulative, may be exercised singularly or concurrently, and shall not be deemed exclusive. If any legal action is brought to enforce any obligations hereunder, the prevailing party shall be entitled to receive its attorneys’ fees, court costs and other collection expenses, in addition to any other relief it may receive. This Agreement is not intended to provide any rights or remedies to any person or entity other than the parties and their respective successors and assigns.

Governing Law; Dispute Resolution. This Agreement shall be construed and enforced in accordance with the laws of the State of California. The parties shall use reasonable efforts to amicably resolve any dispute, claim or controversy arising out of or relating to this Agreement. Any unresolved dispute, claim or controversy arising out of or relating to this Agreement or the breach, termination, enforcement, interpretation or validity thereof, including the determination of the scope or applicability of this clause to arbitrate, shall be determined by arbitration held in San Francisco, California before one neutral arbitrator. THE PARTIES UNDERSTAND AND AGREE THAT THEY ARE WAIVING THEIR RIGHT TO BRING SUCH CLAIMS TO COURT, INCLUDING THE RIGHT TO A JURY TRIAL. The arbitration proceedings shall be administered by JAMS pursuant to its Comprehensive Arbitration Rules and Procedures, which are incorporated herein by reference, as may be modified by this Agreement. The arbitration and proceedings shall be confidential. The arbitrator will issue a detailed written decision and award that shall decide all issues submitted, set forth the legal principles of the opinion, and be final and binding upon the parties. Judgment on the arbitral award may be entered in any court of competent jurisdiction. This clause shall not preclude either party from seeking injunctive or other equitable relief in any court of competent jurisdiction.

NON-DISCLOSURE AND NON-USE OBLIGATIONS. 1. Duty of Confidentiality. Discloser may disclose to Recipient, or Recipient may otherwise receive access to,
Confidential Information (as defined below). Recipient may use the Confidential Information solely to evaluate or
carry out the Potential Business Relationship and for no other purpose. Recipient agrees to hold the Confidential
Information in the strictest confidence. Recipient must protect the Confidential Information from unauthorized use,
access or disclosure using at least the same degree of care Recipient uses to protect its own most sensitive
information, but no less than a commercially reasonable degree of care. Recipient will not disclose any Confidential
Information to any third parties except to Recipient’s officers, directors, employees, affiliates, professional advisors
(i.e. attorneys and accountants), or to such others as necessary to further the Potential Business Relationship, and
only on a need-to-know basis. Recipient will be liable for any violations of this Agreement by any such third party.
2. Confidential Information. As used in this Agreement, “Confidential Information” means all non-public, proprietary or
confidential information or trade secrets regarding Discloser’s prior, existing or proposed business, activities,
experiences, investments, services, products, systems, procedures, safeguards, employees, members, and facilities.
Confidential Information includes, without limitation, (a) financial information, budgets, business results, business
volumes, pricing, strategic plans and forecasts, (b) audit and examination information, including findings, ratings,
enforcement actions and reports, (c) contracts, vendors, practices, policies and procedures, (d) member names or
information, employee names or information, or “NPPI” as defined below, (e) technical data, know-how, formulas,
patterns, computer programs and software (including object and source code), compilations, reports, methods,
strategies, plans, documents, drawings, designs, tools, models, inventions, patent disclosures, and requests for
proposals, and (f) any other information if it would be apparent to a reasonable person that such information is of a
confidential or proprietary nature. Confidential Information may be in oral, visual, written, electronic or other tangible
or intangible form, whether or not marked or designated as "confidential," and includes all notes, analyses, summaries
and other materials Recipient prepares that contain, are based upon or otherwise reflect any of the foregoing.
Confidential Information excludes information that (i) is or becomes generally available to the public other than as a
result of Recipient’s breach of this Agreement; (ii) Recipient obtained on a non-confidential basis from a third-party
who was not legally or contractually restricted from disclosing such information; (iii) was in Recipient’s possession
prior to Discloser’s disclosure; or (iv) was or is independently developed by Recipient without using any Confidential
Information. Notwithstanding, NPPI is always “Confidential Information,” even if it would otherwise be excluded by the
preceding sentence.

4. Compulsory Disclosure. Neither party has any obligation under this Agreement to disclose any Confidential
Information to the other. If Recipient is required by judicial or administrative process to disclose any Confidential
Information, Recipient will notify Discloser in a timely manner (unless otherwise prohibited by law) so that Discloser
may seek, at its expense, a protective order or other remedy. If Recipient remains legally compelled to make such
disclosure, Recipient agrees to (a) disclose only that portion of the Confidential Information that Recipient is required
to disclose; and (b) use reasonable efforts to ensure that such Confidential Information is afforded confidential
treatment.

Return or Destruction of Confidential Information. When this Agreement expires, or sooner at Discloser’s
request, Recipient will promptly, at Discloser’s option, either return or destroy all Confidential Information in
Recipient’s possession, and certify to Discloser in writing that all such Confidential Information has been destroyed.
Notwithstanding, Recipient may retain copies of the Confidential Information to the extent required to comply with
applicable legal and regulatory requirements. All retained Confidential Information will remain subject to the terms
and conditions of this Agreement.

Ownership. Discloser retains all right, title, and interest in and to all Confidential Information, and no disclosure of
Confidential Information will be construed as a license, assignment or other transfer of any such right, title, and
interest to Recipient or any other person.

Term of Agreement. This Agreement will continue for five years from the later of (a) the Effective Date, or (b) the
date Recipient no longer possesses any of Discloser’s Confidential Information. For Confidential Information that is a
trade secret under the laws of any jurisdiction, this Agreement will survive until, if ever, such Confidential Information
loses its trade secret protection other than due to an act or omission by Recipient. For NPPI, Recipient’s obligations
under this Agreement will continue indefinitely.

Remedies. Recipient agrees that any breach of this Agreement will cause injury and irreparable harm to Discloser for
which money damages would be an inadequate remedy. In addition to remedies at law, Discloser will be entitled to
equitable relief as a remedy for any such breach. Recipient waives any claim or defense that Discloser may have an

Definitions.

 “Confidential Information” means all information disclosed during the Disclosure Period by or on behalf of either Party to the other whether disclosed in writing, orally or by inspection and may include, but is not limited to, product designs, patent applications, product and manufacturing technology, supplier data, marketing plans and consumer data, customer lists, research and development data, financial data, costs and expense data, trade secrets, processes, formulae, methods, know-how, techniques and similar information. 
“Disclosing Party” means a Party disclosing Confidential Information according to the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement.
“Receiving Party” means a Party receiving Confidential Information according to the terms and conditions set forth in this Agreement.

Use of Confidential Information. Receiving Party will  protect Confidential Information using at least the same degree of care with which it treats its own Confidential Information, but no less than reasonable care and will (i) not disclose or permit the disclosure of the Disclosing Party’s Confidential Information to a third party without prior written consent of the Disclosing Party; (ii) limit dissemination of the Confidential Information to those of its employees, officers, directors and Affiliates who have a need to know in relation to the Purpose; (iii) not use, or permit the use of, Confidential Information except for the Purpose; and (iv) not decompile, decode, reproduce, redesign, or reverse engineer Confidential Information or any part thereof.

Exclusions.  The obligations of confidentiality assumed by the Receiving Party pursuant to this Agreement shall not apply to any information which (i) was available to the public at the time of disclosure or which subsequently becomes available to the public through no fault of Receiving Party; (ii) was in Receiving Party’s possession without any confidential obligation prior to its receipt as evidenced by written records; (iii) is required to be disclosed by law, provided that Receiving Party promptly notifies Disclosing Party of such requirement to enable Disclosing Party the opportunity to oppose such requirement or seek a protective order; and (iv) was independently developed by the Receiving Party without use of, or reliance upon, any Confidential Information, as evidenced by the Receiving Party’s written records.
It is understood for the purposes of this Agreement that specific information disclosed by either Party to the other shall not be deemed to be available to the public or in the possession of Receiving Party merely because the specific information is embraced by more general information available to the public.  Also, any combination of features or elements relating to Confidential Information shall not be deemed to be within the foregoing enumerated exclusions merely because the individual features are separately in the public domain or in the possession of Receiving Party unless the combination itself or its principle of operation were known publicly or were in the possession of Receiving Party prior to the disclosure of thereof by Disclosing Party.  The burden shall be on Receiving Party to prove applicability of any such exclusions.

Return. Upon termination of this Agreement or upon earlier request by Disclosing Party, Receiving Party will promptly return to Disclosing Party or destroy all documents, other written information and tangible information obtained from Disclosing Party containing Confidential Information without retaining any copies thereof. Upon request by Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party will certify this action in writing.

Governing Law and Remedies.  Either Party shall have the right to seek injunctive relief for a breach of confidentiality without the necessity of proving actual damages.  Any controversy or claim arising out of or relating to this Agreement shall be construed and governed in accordance with the laws of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania, without giving effect to any principles of conflicts of law.

1.     Scope  of   Agreement.     This   Agreement   applies   to   all information about Provider and Provider’s business provided to or obtained  by  Recipient  and  not  generally  known  to  the  public,
whether or not such information is specifically identified as confidential, including without limitation information provided in written, oral or electronic form or obtained through reviews of products, tours or demonstrations, relating to Provider or its employees, businesses, processes or methods, specifications, products, product designs or materials, research, development, testing, production, marketing, business planning, financial information, customer or supplier information, and the like, including information discussed or received prior to the Effective Date, the existence of this Agreement and the fact that information has been made available to Recipient (collectively “Information”).

2.     Purpose.      Recipient   will  use   the  Information  for  the exclusive purpose of conducting business with Provider (or evaluating
the possibility of conducting business with Provider) and will not use the Information for any other purpose.

3.        Limited Disclosure.  Recipient will not transfer or assign the
Information or any portion of the Information to any individual, firm
or  organization  in  any  manner,  including  without  limitation  by
operation of law, without Provider’s prior written permission, except that: (a) Recipient may disclose Information to its officers, directors and employees on a need-to-know basis after explaining Recipient’s obligations   under   this   Agreement  to   such   individuals;   and   (b) Recipient may disclose Information to third-party advisors on a need- to-know basis, provided that before disclosure to any third-party advisor, Recipient will have a written agreement with that party sufficient to require that party to treat Information in accordance with this Agreement.   Recipient will be liable for any breach of this Agreement  by  any  individual,  firm  or  organization  to  whom  it discloses Information.
4.     Standard of Care.  Recipient will protect the Information by using the same degree of care as Recipient uses to prevent the unauthorized disclosure of its own confidential information, but no less than a reasonable degree of care.

5.     Exceptions to Obligations.   Recipient’s obligations of non- use and nondisclosure under this Agreement will not apply to any Information which: (a) has become generally known to the public
through no fault of Recipient; or (b) was known to Recipient before it was obtained from Provider; or (c) has been disclosed to Recipient free of any obligations of confidentiality by a third party who has a right to disclose such Information and did not derive the Information from Provider; or (d) has been independently developed by Recipient without the use of any Information and by individuals who do not have access to the Information.  Recipient has the burden of proof to demonstrate that such Information falls within one of the exceptions listed above.

6.     Limitations on Agreement.  Nothing in this Agreement will be construed or considered: (a) to grant Recipient any rights under any patents, trademarks, copyrights or other intellectual property of Provider; or (b) to permit use of the Information in any way not directly related to the purpose described in Section 2 above. Disclosure of Information pursuant to this Agreement is not “publication” for patent or copyright purposes or a release of Information into the public domain.   No partnership or agency relationship is created by this Agreement.   Neither party has an obligation by virtue of this Agreement to purchase any products or services from the other party or enter into any business relationship.

7.     Samples, Software and Materials.   Recipient may be given access to Information contained in the form of samples, software, materials and the like (collectively “Samples”).  Recipient agrees not to  analyze  or  reverse  engineer  or  have  a  third  party  analyze  or reverse engineer Samples, unless specifically requested by Provider in writing to do so.  Immediately upon Provider’s request, Recipient will destroy or return to Provider all remaining Samples, regardless of condition.

8.     Return of Information.   Promptly upon Provider’s request, Recipient will destroy or return to Provider all documents containing Information   and   will   delete   all   electronic   documents   or   files containing Information.  If Recipient has included Information in any of its internally prepared documents, Recipient will not be obligated to return those documents to Provider, provided that Recipient: (a) collects and segregates all such documents; or (b) destroys all such documents; and, in either case (c) certifies in writing to Provider that the appropriate action has been taken.

9.     Judicial or Administrative Action.  In the event Recipient is required by law or judicial or administrative process to disclose Information,  Recipient  will:  (a)  promptly  notify  Provider;  (b) cooperate as reasonably requested by Provider if Provider elects to oppose such disclosure; and (c) at Provider’s cost and expense, take all reasonable steps necessary to limit disclosure and obtain a protective order prior to disclosure.

10.  Injunctive Relief.  Recipient agrees that a violation of this Agreement may cause irreparable harm to Provider and that Provider will be entitled to injunctive relief and specific performance, in addition to any other remedies available at law or in equity.

11. Disclaimer of Warranty.   Provider provides Information without warranties of any kind, and will not be liable for any damages arising out of the use of Information disclosed under this Agreement.

.

(i)	the singular includes the plural and vice versa, and a gender includes other genders;

(ii)	another grammatical form of a defined word or expression has a corresponding meaning;

(iii)	a reference to a clause or paragraph is to a clause or paragraph of this agreement; 

(iv)	the meaning of general words is not limited by specific examples introduced by including, for example or similar expressions;

(v)	any agreement, representation, warranty or indemnity by two or more parties (including where two or more persons are included in the same defined term) binds them jointly and severally; 

(vi)	any agreement, representation, warranty or indemnity in favour of two or more parties (including where two or more persons are included in the same defined term) is for the benefit of them jointly and severally;

The Recipient must

(a)	keep the Information confidential;

(b)	not disclose the Information without the prior written consent of the Disclosing Party, except as permitted in paragraph 3, paragraph 4 or paragraph 5;

(c)	not use the Information, directly or indirectly, for any purpose other than to evaluate the Transaction; and

(d)	ensure that its Representatives observe and perform all of the Recipient's obligations as if they had signed this agreement.

Disclosure to representatives	
The Recipient may disclose the Information to its Representatives subject to the condition that they:

(b)	are informed by the Recipient of the confidential nature of the Information; and 

(c)	are obliged to observe the restrictions set out in this agreement.

The Recipient is responsible for any breach of the provisions of this agreement by any of its Representatives.

Disclosure required by law
If the Recipient, its affiliates or anyone to whom the Recipient discloses the Information pursuant to this agreement is required by law, regulation or the rules of any stock exchange on which that entity's shares are traded to disclose any of the Information, the Recipient must provide the Disclosing Party with prompt written notice.  In appropriate circumstances, the Disclosing Party may seek a protective order or other appropriate remedy and/or waive compliance with the provisions of this agreement, and the Recipient must consent to and assist the Disclosing Party in obtaining any protective order or other appropriate remedy that the Disclosing Party or any of its affiliates may seek for the purpose of preventing disclosure of any of the Information; provided, however, that nothing in this agreement prevents the Recipient, its affiliates or its Representatives from complying with their respective legal obligations or imposes liability on them for doing so.  If the Recipient, its affiliates or Representatives makes any disclosure pursuant to this paragraph, they must disclose only that portion of the Information which they are legally required to disclose.

If no transaction between the Recipient and the Disclosing Party is effected after the Information is furnished to the Recipient, or if the Disclosing Party so requests at any time for any reason whatever, the Recipient must promptly and, in any event, within five Business Days of receipt of a written request from the Disclosing Party, deliver to the Disclosing Party or, at the option of the Recipient, destroy, all Information in tangible form, and so far as it is reasonably practicable to do so, delete any Information from any computer, word processor or other device in the possession, custody or control of the Recipient or its Representatives.  The Recipient and its Representatives are not required to delete or alter back-up copies of computer files created in the ordinary course of business, although if such copies are restored from back-up files after the Disclosing Party has requested their return or destruction, they must be immediately deleted except to the extent permitted by paragraph 5. Damages not an adequate remedy

The obligations of the Recipients under this agreement continue to apply for a period of two three (32) years from the date of disclosure of the Information.

Background. The Parties intend to engage in discussions concerning a possible business relationship and each Party may disclose or deliver to the other Party and its directors, officers, employees, agents or advisors (collectively, “Representatives”) confidential information to enable the other Party to evaluate the feasibility of the business relationship, and to perform its obligations under related agreements (the “Purpose”). The Parties have entered into this Agreement to assure the confidentiality of such information. As used herein, the Party disclosing Proprietary Information is referred to as the “Disclosing Party” and the Party receiving such Proprietary Information is referred to as  “Recipient.”

Proprietary Information. The term “Proprietary Information” shall mean information of the Disclosing Party, including, but not limited to, trade secrets, know-how, proprietary, technical, developmental, operating, financial, performance, cost, process, client and prospect information, and all samples, models, evaluation boards, reports, tables, data and prototypes containing or disclosing such information, that is (a) marked or accompanied by documents clearly and conspicuously designating the information as “confidential” or the equivalent, (b) identified by the Disclosing Party in writing as confidential before, during or promptly after the disclosure  or (c) information that, given the nature of the information or the circumstances surrounding its disclosure, a reasonable person would understand to be confidential. “Proprietary Information” shall be deemed to include notes, analyses, compilations, interpretations, memoranda or other documents prepared by Recipient or its Representatives which contain, reflect or are based upon, Proprietary Information of the Disclosing Party.

Use and Disclosure of Proprietary Information. Recipient and its Representatives shall hold in confidence, and shall not disclose, any Proprietary Information of the Disclosing Party; provided, however, that (i) Recipient may make any disclosure of such information to which the Disclosing Party gives its prior written consent, and (ii) Proprietary Information may be disclosed by  Recipient to its Representatives who need to know such information in connection with the Purpose and who are informed of the confidential nature of such information, the terms of this Agreement, and who agree to keep such information confidential. Recipient shall be responsible for any breach of this Agreement by its Representatives, and agrees, at its sole expense, to take reasonable measures to restrain its Representatives from unauthorized disclosure or use of the Proprietary Information. Recipient shall use the Proprietary Information only for the Purpose, except upon receipt of prior written consent of the Disclosing Party. Neither Party shall disassemble, dismantle, redesign or reverse engineer any Proprietary Information of the other Party.

Limitation on Obligations. The obligations specified in Section 3 above shall not apply to Proprietary Information that: (a) is or becomes generally known to the public through no wrongful act or omission on the part of Recipient; (b) is rightfully in Recipient’s possession at the time of disclosure otherwise than as a result of Recipient’s breach of any legal obligation to the Disclosing Party; (c) becomes known to Recipient through sources (other than the Disclosing Party) having the legal right to disclose such Proprietary Information; (d) is independently developed by Recipient without reference to or reliance upon the Proprietary Information; or (e) is required to be disclosed by Recipient to comply with applicable laws or governmental regulations, provided that Recipient provides prior written notice of such disclosure to the Disclosing Party and takes reasonable and lawful actions to avoid and minimize the extent of such disclosure.

Ownership of Proprietary Information. The Disclosing Party is and shall remain the exclusive owner of its Proprietary Information and all patent, copyright, trade secret, trademark, domain name and other intellectual property rights therein. No license or conveyance of any such rights to  Recipient is granted or implied under this Agreement.

Return of Proprietary Information. Recipient shall, upon the written request of the Disclosing Party, return to the Disclosing Party or destroy all Proprietary Information it received hereunder. Notwithstanding the return or destruction of the Proprietary Information, Recipient and its Representatives will continue to be bound by their confidentiality and other obligations in this Agreement.

No Representation or Warranty. Each Party warrants that it has the right to make the disclosures contemplated by this Agreement NO OTHER WARRANTIES ARE MADE BY EITHER PARTY UNDER THIS AGREEMENT. Each Party acknowledges and agrees that all Proprietary Information is provided without any representation or warranty, express or implied, as to the accuracy or completeness thereof. Only those representations and warranties which are made in a definitive agreement entered into by the Parties, when, as and if executed, and subject to such limitations and restrictions as may be specified therein, will have any legal effect. This Agreement shall not be onstrued to be an obligation to enter into any definitive agreement or to result in any claim by one Party against the other for reimbursement of cost for any efforts expended with respect to the Purpose. No contract providing for any transaction contemplated by the Parties shall be deemed to exist between the Parties unless and until a definitive agreement has been executed.

(d) The provisions of this Agreement are necessary for the protection of the business and goodwill of the Parties and are considered by the Parties to be reasonable for such purpose. Recipient agrees that any breach of this Agreement may cause the Disclosing Party substantial and irreparable damages and, therefore, in the event of any such breach or threatened breach, in addition to other remedies which may be available at law, the Disclosing Party shall have the right to seek specific performance and other injunctive and equitable relief.
